Church fire in Nantes, France: Diocesan volunteers admit that arson is usually good and silent - NEWS
July 26 (Reuters) According to foreign media reports, on July 18, the famous Cathedral of St. Peter and St. Paul, a treasure of religious and historical buildings in Nantes, France, was severely damaged in a fire and the large organ was completely destroyed.
On the 26th local time, the prosecutor of Nantes announced that a parish volunteer responsible for protecting the cathedral had been charged with " arson and destruction. "
He had admitted that he had set fire to the church.
According to the report, local prosecutor Senas said that the 39-year-old parish volunteer from Rwanda admitted that he had set fire to three places in the cathedral at night.
The man's lawyer said the arsonists now regret doing this.
This man entered France by way of refuge a few years ago, took refuge in the parish where the fire occurred, and was admitted in the church.
The prosecution pointed out that he had recently tried to renew his visa and was in dialogue with the police about it.
But the church said it still couldn't believe that the normally kind, smiling, but untalkative believer would destroy the church he loved so much.
On the day of the fire on July 18, the volunteer had been questioned and investigated by the police because of illogical problems in the narrative, but he was later released.
The picture shows firefighters carrying out rescue at the scene.
On the evening of the 25th, the man was summoned again after professional engineers from the laboratory of the Paris Central Police obtained new evidence.
This time, the man admitted to arson.
It was reported that if convicted of intentional arson and destruction, the suspect could face 10 years' imprisonment and a fine of 150,000 euros.
It was reported that the fire caused serious damage to the Cathedral of St. Pierre and St. Paul. The organ in the church was completely burned down and the colored glass windows behind the organ were also severely damaged.
Brunet, the chief architect of France's historic buildings, believes that conservative estimates suggest that the restoration of Nantes Cathedral will take at least three years.
Comprehensive news: US unilateralism undermines bilateral relations International public opinion supports China's countermeasures against the US - Xinhua News
Xinhua News Agency, Beijing, July 26 - An overseas correspondent from Xinhua News Agency reported: On the morning of July 24, the Chinese Foreign Ministry informed the US Embassy in China that China had decided to revoke the permission for the establishment and operation of the US Consulate General in Chengdu and put forward specific requirements for the Consulate General to stop all business and activities.
International public opinion believes that the unilateral measures taken by the United States have caused serious distress to China-US relations. It is legitimate and necessary for China to respond to the unreasonable provocations of the United States and to take countermeasures.
Andrés Bolx, director of the China Research Center of the Institute of International Studies of the University of Chile, said that the unilateral measures taken by the United States have damaged the bridge of understanding between the two peoples and caused a crisis in the relations between the two major countries.
China's notification to the United States of the closure of its Consulate General in Chengdu is a countermeasure to the unilateral measures taken by the United States and is in line with diplomatic practice.
Patricio Giusto, a professor at the Catholic University of Argentina and director of the Center for Arab-China Studies, believes that China's above-mentioned decision is a legitimate and necessary countermeasure against the previous provocations of the United States and is not aimed at ordinary Americans.
The United States is trying to divert the attention of the American public by pressuring China to cover up its inability to cope with the COVID-19 pandemic.
Bambang Suryono, chairman of the Asian Innovation Research Center, an Indonesian think tank, said that the provocative diplomatic posture taken by the United States has caused serious distress to China-US relations and bilateral relations are facing serious challenges.
China's notification to the United States of the closure of its Consulate General in Chengdu is a normal countermeasure and conforms to diplomatic practice. It not only reflects China's principled position of resolutely safeguarding its own interests, but also reflects the reasonableness, advantages and justice of China's diplomacy.
Tanzanian current affairs commentator Francis Semwinza said that China's above-mentioned decision is a legitimate and necessary response to the US provocation.
For China-US relations to return to normal, the US should proactively improve its relations with China and stop interfering in China's internal affairs.
The United States should focus on how to achieve win-win economic and political results with China and how to benefit the two peoples and the international community as a whole.
Ali Yusuf, executive director of the Federation of Arab-China Friendship Associations headquartered in Sudan, said that the countermeasures that China was forced to take are a legitimate and necessary response to the unreasonable actions of the US, in line with international law and the basic norms governing international relations, as well as diplomatic practice.
Earlier, the US demanded the closure of the Chinese Consulate General in Houston in serious violation of international law and the basic norms governing international relations.
We hope that the US can rescind its previous decision and create the necessary conditions for the return of bilateral relations to normal.
Singapore's Lianhe Zaobao said in an editorial that the greater strategic intention of the United States is to contain China and prevent China from continuing to rise.
In the face of the gradual pressure from the United States, although China is very reluctant to see China-US relations continue to deteriorate, it has to take countermeasures.
