The Federal Aviation Administration said that it has so far received four reports of air parking of the engines of the 737NG and 737Classic aircraft, so it has made an emergency inspection request for the passenger aircraft that have been parked continuously for seven days or more and the passenger aircraft that have flown less than 11 times so far after returning to flight.
The Federal Aviation Administration warned that if the fifth-stage check valves of all two engines were corroded, they could get stuck in the open position, causing the aircraft to completely lose power and unable to restart the engine.
The aviation regulator ordered that if the check valve was found to be corroded, air operators must replace the key component before the aircraft was put into service again.
Boeing responded later that day that the COVID-19 pandemic had reduced travel demand, and many passenger planes had been sealed or used less, making " check valves more vulnerable to corrosion. "
Boeing also said that it has advised air operators to inspect the passenger aircraft covered by the directive, and if problems are found, Boeing will provide assistance in repairing and replacing check valves.
The Associated Press reported that airliners owned by major US air carriers usually fly multiple times a day, but a large number of airliners were grounded after the COVID-19 outbreak. With the recent slow growth in passenger travel demand, some airliners have returned to operation.
The FAA did not release details of the four air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents later on the 24th.
The airline operator said in a statement that on its way from Seattle, Washington, to Austin, Texas, on July 15, one of its engines suddenly failed, and the plane finally made a successful emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines said it had replaced the aircraft's engines and had checked the engines of six aircraft in accordance with FAA instructions.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines respectively said on the 24th that their aircraft had no engine failure associated with the air check valve.
Four American Airlines aircraft will be inspected, and 28 United Airlines aircraft will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect its 20 aircraft, but did not say if there had been any engine failure.
