The United States launched its first countervailing investigation against China with " RMB exchange rate undervalued "
In response to the recent announcement by the United States Department of Commerce, it decided to launch an anti-dumping countervailing investigation on tie (harness) products originating in China, and to launch an investigation on the project of " RMB exchange rate undervaluation. "
China's Ministry of Commerce pointed out that this is the first time that the United States has opened an investigation into the so-called " undervaluation of the RMB exchange rate " in a countervailing case, which China firmly opposes.
China's Ministry of Commerce issued a special press release on the evening of the 23rd, saying that China implements a managed floating exchange rate system based on market supply and demand and adjusted with reference to a basket of currencies, and the market plays a decisive role in the formation of the exchange rate.
The press release stressed that, on the whole, the RMB exchange rate is at a reasonable equilibrium level and has not been underestimated.
Since 2005, the RMB has appreciated by more than 17% against the US dollar.
According to data released by the Bank for International Settlements, from early 2005 to May 2020, the RMB nominal effective exchange rate appreciated by 38% and the real effective exchange rate by 49%, making it the strongest currency among the G20 economies and one of the most appreciated currencies in the world.
The Ministry of Commerce pointed out that the exchange rate issue is beyond the competence of members to conduct countervailing investigations in accordance with the rules of the World Trade Organization.
The United States amended its regulations in February this year to conduct countervailing investigations on other countries' exchange rates, which has been suspected of violating WTO rules and has been opposed by many parties.
The press release said that even in accordance with US regulations, the content of the applicant's complaint contained a large number of errors and did not have the necessary countervailing elements such as financial support, grant of benefits and exclusivity.
China urges the US to abide by existing international rules and stop conducting countervailing investigations into the so-called " undervaluation of the RMB exchange rate. "
Affected by the further rise in tensions between China and the US, the offshore and onshore RMB depreciated sharply against the US dollar on the 22nd day, and both fell below the threshold of RMB 7.0 against the US dollar.
Whether the US Department of Commerce's move is intended to push up the RMB deserves attention.
The spot exchange rate of RMB against the US dollar rose above the 7.0 mark on the 23rd and closed at 6.9961.
The official-regulated midpoint rate of the RMB against the US dollar was lowered by 17 basic points on the 24th, at 6.9938.
