Lewis Family: John Lewis is a soldier " fighting for the weakest "
Congressman John Lewis, a civil rights fighter, was remembered as " fighting for the weakest " at a memorial service for him on Saturday (July 25).
Lewis's public memorial service has been held in Alabama since Saturday.
There were two memorial services on the first day.
At a public memorial service at the University of Troy in Alabama on Saturday, Lewis's five brothers and sisters and a nephew spoke of him as a loving, fearless, family-oriented man.
" He devoted his life to helping others, " Lewis's youngest brother, Henry " Grant " Lewis, said at the meeting.
Samuel Lewis said his mother had warned John " not to get into trouble, not to get into trouble. "
He added that John did not heed his mother's warning, saying, " We all know that John is always going to get into trouble, always getting into trouble, but that's because he insists on the right thing, and that's a good trouble. "
Lewis's brothers and sisters reminded people at the memorial service that John's most famous argument was to create " good trouble, " that is, not to avoid provoking trouble for the sake of justice.
John applied to Troy University in Troy, Alabama, where he was born, but Troy University, then an all-white school, rejected his application.
John Lewis, who preached the Gospel to chickens on his farm as a child, eventually earned a degree in religion and philosophy from Fisk University.
Years later, the University of Troy awarded Lewis an honorary doctorate.
Senator Doug Jones from Alabama said the current protesters were " protesting peacefully and non-violently, " as Lewis did in the civil rights movement.
Jones said: " Even if President Trump hit a boat and described all the protesters as a mob, he was wrong.
The protesters are patriots who want the United States to move towards a more egalitarian country. "
A six-day series of events to commemorate Lewis will culminate this week at a funeral in Georgia.
Lewis's coffin was parked at a public memorial service at the University of Troy on Saturday to pay tribute to the civil rights pioneer.
Later Saturday, a private ceremony paid tribute to him in a chapel in Selma, Alabama, followed by a public memorial service.
On Sunday, Lewis's body will pass through the Edmund Pettus Bridge in Selma.
In 1965, he and protesters demanding black voting rights were severely beaten in front of the bridge by Alabama police, who also fired tear gas at protesters.
Lewis was almost killed at the time.
This day later became known as " Bloody Sunday. "
Lewis's body will be transported to Montgomery, the capital of Alabama.
Mayor Steven Reed encouraged people to line up on the sidewalk to complete the final journey with Lewis.
Meanwhile, officials asked the public to wear face masks and maintain social distance when participating in the activities.
Alabama Governor Kay Ivey ordered the flag to be flown at half-mast on Saturday and Sunday in honor of Lewis.
