Representatives of China-US trade talks met in August
On the 25th, Hong Kong's South China Morning Post quoted an anonymous person familiar with the matter as reporting that the head of China's trade negotiation team, Vice Premier Liu He of the State Council, and the co-leader of the US team and trade representative Lai Haizhe are expected to hold formal talks in August to assess the implementation of the first phase of the China-US trade agreement.
The report said that although China has significantly increased its purchases of US agricultural products in the past few months, due to factors such as the virus epidemic, China's purchases are still some distance from the amount promised in the trade agreement.
Analysts say the recent US-China closure of each other's consulates, along with other disputes, could undermine any progress in trade between the two sides.
The first phase of the China-US trade agreement came into effect one month after it was signed on January 15. The agreement stipulates that the high-level trade framework group of the two sides should meet every six months.
People familiar with the matter said the meeting would be " an important turning point " for both sides to assess the progress of the agreement.
However, this person also said that if tensions between the US and China lead to a lack of willingness for talks at this time, the two sides may agree that the conference call between Lai Haizhe and Liu He on May 8 has already met the semi-annual terms of the trade agreement.
Since the beginning of this year, China-US relations have deteriorated rapidly, with disputes between the two sides including the origin of the COVID-19 virus, trade, Hong Kong, Xinjiang, the South China Sea and ideology.
US President Donald Trump boasted about his achievements in the first phase of the agreement at the beginning of the year, but his attitude has changed recently.
He said at the White House press conference on August 23 that although China has recently purchased a record number of American corn in one day and bought a lot of soybeans, " this trade agreement is not as meaningful to me as it was when it was reached. "
An anonymous Beijing government adviser also said that a new round of trade talks is unlikely due to the poor relationship between China and the US, and that " trade issues have lost weight in China-US relations. "
However, he revealed that China's economic and trade-related units still met on the 23rd to discuss a series of issues, including how to increase imports from the United States. " We have tried our best to buy, so any additional purchases will be difficult. "
Peng Jining, vice-president of the National Committee on US-China Trade, said that maintaining the momentum of the first phase of the agreement was " more important than ever " and said that China had made progress in further opening up its financial markets to US companies this year.
An analyst at Plenum, an independent research firm, said: " It's better to talk than not to talk, although it may only be seen as routine. "
