France increases military investment in space - Xinhuanet
French Defense Minister Florence Palley said on the 24th that France will increase its space defense budget by hundreds of millions of euros and develop space military forces in order to prevent " unfriendly moves " that other countries may make in outer space.
Palley told Le Provence on the same day that between 2019 and 2025, the expenditure budget for French space military projects will increase from the previously proposed 3.6 billion euros (about 4.2 billion US dollars) to 4.3 billion euros (5 billion US dollars).
According to the French Military Planning Act 2019-2025, approved by the French Parliament in 2018, France is expected to upgrade its existing observation and communication satellites, launch three electromagnetic listening satellites, and improve the modernization of its space surveillance radar.
French President Emmanuel Macron announced last July that a military space command and an " aviation and space force " would be established within the French Air Force.
Palley said she would officially announce the establishment of the space force later when she visited a military academy in Salon, Provence.
Palley said the space force is part of the Air Force and will have 500 personnel by 2025.
" The idea that space served the common interests of science is gone forever. Now space is a place where countries compete for global hegemony, " she said.
Palley reiterated Macron's previous statement that France has no intention of provoking an arms race.
" We are by no means engaged in an arms race, but it is my responsibility to fully understand the threats we may face. "
Palley recalled the surveillance of a military satellite shared by France and Italy in 2017.
She said that " peeping " was a Russian satellite.
Russia denies this claim.
Palley said France would " soon " have small patrol satellites capable of detecting and targeting " the black hands behind those unfriendly moves. "
French media believe that France seeks to establish a space force because US President Donald Trump asked the US Department of Defense to draft a bill on the establishment of the Pacific Air Force last February.
Trump signed the National Defense Authorization Act last December, approving the establishment of the Pacific Air Force, the sixth military force in the United States.
Some experts are concerned that these measures by the US have accelerated the pace of US space militarization and may trigger a new round of space arms race.
