Xinhua News (Reporter Yang Zhaokui) The " China Shared Accommodation Development Report 2020 " (hereinafter referred to as the " Report ") released by the Sharing Economic Research Center of the National Information Center shows that due to the impact of the epidemic, the turnover of China's shared accommodation market fell by 72.1% year on year in the first five months of 2020.
However, the shared accommodation market began to pick up in March, and the market turnover, order volume and reception number gradually recovered.
The Report shows that the transaction volume of the shared accommodation market decreased significantly. On the one hand, due to the sharp decline in the demand for travel accommodation under epidemic prevention and control, the volume of orders decreased sharply. The total number of orders in the first five months decreased by 65% year on year, and the number of reception visits decreased by 63% year on year. On the other hand, the weakness of demand also led to a marked decline in night prices, with the average night price in the first five months falling by 16% year on year.
However, the market turnover in March, April and May increased by 78%, 1999% and 35% respectively; the number of orders increased by 141%, 152% and 50% respectively; and the number of visitors increased by 81%, 112% and 28% respectively.
The report points out that the development of the shared accommodation industry has been promising for a long time, but there are still many uncertainties in the near future.
In this regard, Yu Fengxia, deputy director of the Sharing Economy Research Center of the National Information Center, told the reporter of the Workers' Daily that the development of shared accommodation needs stronger policy support. On the one hand, we need to do a good job in the implementation of the policies already introduced in the previous period, further strengthen policy dissemination and focus on creating a better business environment; on the other hand, we need to further strengthen policy guidance and support from such aspects as stimulating consumer demand, enriching the supply of tourism accommodation services, innovating service methods and strengthening cooperation between the government and platform enterprises.
