Israel Strengthens Prevention and Control of Repeated Epidemics - NEWS
2020-07-26 04: 56: 44 Source: Guangming Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Executive Editor: Wang Sishuo
Israel strengthens prevention and control of repeated outbreaks
At the beginning of the SARS outbreak, Israel's prevention and control measures achieved remarkable results.
However, with the gradual lifting of prevention and control measures, the number of people diagnosed with COVID-19 pneumonia in Israel has increased significantly recently, and the Israeli government has repeatedly taken urgent measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On February 28, the first case of COVID-19 pneumonia was confirmed in Israel, which quickly took measures to close all entry and exit ports, suspend non-essential industries, switch schools to online classes, restrict public transportation and non-essential social activities, block epidemic-hit cities, and the military and police jointly maintain prevention and control measures.
This series of measures quickly achieved positive results. By mid-May, the number of new confirmed cases of COVID-19 pneumonia in Israel fell to the single digits.
As the epidemic has been brought under control, Israel's prevention and control measures have been completely unblocked, and the number of newly diagnosed cases of COVID-19 pneumonia has gradually rebounded since June.
Especially since the beginning of July, the spread of the epidemic has been accelerating.
In recent days, there were more than 1,500 new cases per day in Israel for eight days, and as of the time of writing on July 25, there were 916 new cases on that day.
As of July 25, Israel had 59,745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths.
Faced with the rapid rebound of the epidemic, the Israeli government has repeatedly taken urgent measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On July 6, after the number of confirmed cases exceeded 30,000, the Israeli government closed gymnasiums, swimming pools, bars, nightclubs and other public entertainment venues, and introduced a policy of restricting public transportation, stipulating that the maximum number of passengers per bus should not exceed 20.
On the 17th, the Israeli government announced a series of new restrictive measures, including the implementation of the " economic reform " on weekends, stipulating that the " economic reform " will be implemented from 17: 00 every Friday to 5: 00 every Sunday.
During this period, people can go out, but places such as shops, shopping centers, barber shops, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while basic service places such as supermarkets and pharmacies will remain open.
At the same time, gatherings of more than 10 people will be banned on all dates and hours, gymnasiums, studios and other places will be closed, restaurants and cafes will be banned from eating, and only take-out service will be allowed.
Meanwhile, the Israeli people did not pay enough attention to the seriousness of the epidemic and failed to join forces with the government in fighting the epidemic.
After repeated outbreaks in Israel, many people took to the streets to protest because the government's prevention and control measures affected their own economic interests.
On July 11, tens of thousands of people held a demonstration in Tel Aviv, arguing that the anti-SARS policy affected the economy.
On the evening of the 21st, thousands more protesters gathered in front of Prime Minister Netanyahu's official residence in Jerusalem to protest that Prime Minister Netanyahu banned restaurants, coffee halls and other prevention and control measures without compensation.
In addition, many people do not observe the regulations on wearing masks and maintaining a safe social distance of two meters when outdoors. In order to avoid being fined by the police for not wearing masks, many people only wear masks on their chin or hang them on their wrists.
During the repeated epidemic, the school was the hardest-hit area for the spread of the COVID-19 virus. According to the reporter's recent visit to the kindergarten, the teachers and students of the kindergarten did not wear face masks as required by the government, nor did they maintain a safe social distance of two meters from each other, laying hidden dangers for a large number of teachers and students infected with the virus.
Professor Elie Waxman, a member of the Expert Advisory Group on Combating the Epidemic of the Israeli National Security Council, believes that Israel is moving towards a " dangerous situation, " pointing out that the current epidemic prevention and control measures taken by Israel are not enough and that all leisure and recreational places and summer schools should be closed in order to control the further spread of the epidemic.
Waxman said that Israel lacks an overall plan to combat the epidemic. The parliament and all government departments should abandon their respective interests as soon as possible, reach agreement on combating the epidemic and formulate clear steps including relevant restrictive measures in different departments.
